// Celtic Gods — the canonical 12 deities of the Tuatha Dé Danann — SEO funnel.
// /gab44/celtic-gods (index) + /gab44/celtic-gods/{slug}.
//
// Peer to Olympians, Norse Gods, Hindu Devas, Egyptian Gods. Closes the
// fifth great mythological pantheon on gab44 — and the one most directly
// lashed to the Wheel of the Year sabbats already on the site (Imbolc is
// literally Brigid's day, Lughnasadh is named for Lugh, Samhain is the
// Morrígan's threshold, Beltane was the fire-festival of the cattle-driving
// the herds between two bonfires which the Tuatha taught the Milesians).
//
// Three-family taxonomy:
//  - Sovereigns of the Tuatha (Dagda, Danu, Lugh, Nuada) — gold / emerald;
//    the all-father with the cauldron, the all-mother of the people, the
//    many-skilled sun-king, the silver-armed first king.
//  - Trí Dée Dána · craft & inspiration (Brigid, Ogma, Goibniu, Aengus) —
//    copper / silver / bronze; the canonical Three Gods of Craft plus
//    Aengus the love-poet — the foundation of civilization.
//  - Threshold & Wild (Cernunnos, Manannán mac Lir, Morrígan, Macha) —
//    stag-brown / sea-blue / raven-black / blood-red; the horned lord of
//    the beasts, the sea-otherworld guide, the battle-crow, the horse-queen
//    of sovereignty.
//
// Source-honest from the Lebor Gabála Érenn (Book of the Taking of Ireland,
// 11th c. compilation of much older oral material), Cath Maige Tuired (The
// Second Battle of Moytura — the foundational Tuatha-vs-Fomorians text),
// the Táin Bó Cúailnge (the Cattle Raid of Cooley, Ireland's national epic),
// Tochmarc Étaíne, the Ulster Cycle, the Mythological Cycle, the Welsh
// Four Branches of the Mabinogi (12th c.), the Acallam na Senórach, the
// Dindshenchas (place-name lore), Caesar's De Bello Gallico Book 6 (the
// Gaulish-gods evidence c. 50 BCE), the Pillar of the Boatmen inscription
// (Paris, c. 14-37 CE — the canonical Cernunnos source), the Gundestrup
// Cauldron (Denmark, c. 100 BCE — Iron Age Celtic iconography), Marie-Louise
// Sjoestedt's Gods and Heroes of the Celts (1940), Proinsias Mac Cana's
// Celtic Mythology (1970), Miranda Aldhouse-Green's archaeological work.
// Shadow-honest: 19th-c. Celtic Twilight romantic-revival flattening,
// modern "Celtic spirituality" commercial commodification, neo-Druid
// reinvention from 18th-c. Iolo Morganwg forgeries, Wiccan
// re-syncretization without lineage acknowledgment, Riverdance / Lord-of-
// the-Dance Hallmark-Celticism, the Christian erasure of the Morrígan
// (sanitized into "queen Mab" of Shakespeare), the Brigid-as-just-a-saint
// erasure of her pre-Christian goddess-status, the white-nationalist
// co-option of Cernunnos by far-right neopagan groups.

