    the_gift: 'The Morrígan gives the *permission to prophesy doom honestly*. The Cath-Maige-Tuired *I shall not see a world that will be dear to me* prophecy is the cosmic-permission to *speak the actual end-of-an-order without flinching*, to *be the figure in the room who names the dissolution that everyone else is denying*, to *hold the prophecy-of-doom as the work-of-clearing-the-field-for-the-next-cycle* rather than as nihilism. And the *triple-form Morrígna* gift: the cosmic-permission to be *three-things-at-once* (the war-strategist, the prophetic-seer, the sovereignty-conferring-queen) — the recognition that *integrity-as-a-warrior-goddess requires-all-three-forms*, not just one. And the *cosmic-marriage-at-the-ford-on-Samhain* gift: the cosmic-permission to *enter sacred-strategic-alliances that do-not-require-everyday-cohabitation* — the recognition that some of the *deepest unions* are the *cosmic-festival-night* ones that *sanctify the coming-work* and then *return each to their own seat*. And the *crow-on-Cú-Chulainn\'s-shoulder* gift: the willingness to be the *psychopomp-figure* who *confirms-that-the-warrior-is-ready-to-die* — the patron of *the dignity-of-death-in-context*, of the *honored-passing*.',
    the_shadow: 'The Morrígan was *more-aggressively-Christianized-and-demonized* than most Celtic deities — her *unsanitized power*, her *sexual dimensions* (the Dagda-ford-union), and her *prophetic-doom* register were *too-direct* for the medieval-Christian framework, and she was largely *not-syncretized-into-a-saint* (as Brigid was) but *suppressed-and-demonized*. The other shadow: her *Morgan le Fay* descendant in Welsh-Arthurian medieval-romance was *increasingly-villainized* across the cycles — the early Geoffrey-of-Monmouth Morgen is a *positive-healer-and-queen-of-Avalon*, but the later-Vulgate-Cycle and Malory Morgan le Fay is a *witch-villain who plots against Arthur* (and the most-prominent surviving Morrígan-descendant is therefore a *Shakespeare-villainess* register). The third shadow: the *modern-Wiccan-revival* of the Morrígan (notably in the 1990s-2010s) has *over-domesticated* her into a *therapist-archetype-goddess* (the *Goddess-of-Sovereignty / Goddess-of-Reclaiming-Your-Power*), often *stripping the actual-battle-and-doom registers* in favor of a *empowerment-coaching* framework that misses the foundational *Cath-Maige-Tuired-end-of-the-world-prophecy* register. The fourth shadow: the *triple-Morrígna* (Morrígan, Badb, Macha-or-Nemain) has been *flattened* in modern revival into a *single-Morrígan-figure*, often *over-identified-with-the-Badb* (the carrion-crow) alone; the *Macha* and *Nemain* sisters are *almost-never-named* in popular discussion, despite being foundational to the actual triple-structure (see the Macha separate entry). The fifth shadow: the *bean-sidhe / banshee* and the *bean-nighe / washer-at-the-ford* folk-survivals are *almost-always-discussed* without acknowledgment that they are *direct half-Christianized-Morrígan survivals* — the wailing-female-spirit-of-death is the *Badb-shriek-over-the-battlefield* transposed-into-the-family-context, and the *spectral-woman-washing-blood-stained-clothes-by-a-river* is the *Morrígan-at-the-ford* preserved-in-fragmentary-folk-tradition; this erasure removes the *Celtic-deity-lineage* of these well-known folk-figures.',
